          { label: 'Why families fell fastest', text: 'The share of families and children dropped to its lowest since 2012 — largely because most were asylum seekers, and asylum is currently unavailable.' },
          { label: 'Enforcement vs. asylum', text: 'The core dispute is not border security itself (broadly popular) but the fate of asylum: whether it should be suspended, restored, or reformed by Congress.' },
          { label: 'Courts will decide a lot', text: 'The asylum suspension and “metering” are in litigation; how courts rule will shape what is permanently allowed at the border.' },
          { label: 'The backlog persists', text: 'Even with low crossings, immigration courts carry a large backlog of pending cases, so “the border is quiet” does not mean the system is resolved.' }
