          { label: 'The per-country bottleneck', text: 'Per-country caps mean applicants from large countries can wait years or decades for the same green card — a structural issue distinct from total numbers.' },
          { label: 'The wage question', text: 'Whether H-1B mainly fills genuine high-skill shortages or supplies lower-wage labor is the empirical heart of the fight; the 2025 fee tries to tilt it toward higher wages.' },
          { label: 'Where reforms would come from', text: 'The cap, per-country limits, and green-card structure are set by Congress; fees, selection rules (lottery vs. wage-based), and enforcement run through USCIS and the executive; courts weigh challenges.' }
